                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/7113.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-04-12T14:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 12, 1913—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>181. My March 20, 8 p.m., from Vera Cruz. The Minister for Foreign Affairs
                    requests me to secure from the Department a statement as to the stay of American
                    war vessels in Mexican ports beyond the time permitted by Mexican law, which is
                    imperative in this matter, leaving no discretion to the Government. Mr. de la
                    Barra says his Government would be greatly embarrassed if the press should
                    notice the provisions of the law.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry Lane Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
